

Follow these steps exactly:

1. Stop the Background Process (No Admin Needed)
Since you started the process as a standard user, you can stop it without Admin:

Open PowerShell ISE (the regular blue window).

Paste this command and press Enter:

PowerShell
Get-Process powershell | Where-Object {$_.CommandLine -like "*kl.ps1*"} | Stop-Process -Force
This specifically kills the keylogger without closing your current PowerShell window.

2. Remove the Startup File
This is the file that makes it "re-appear" after a reboot.

Press Windows Key + R to open the Run box.

Type shell:startup and hit Enter.

A folder window will pop up. Find the file named kl_auto (it has a small arrow on the icon).

Right-click it and select Delete.

3. Delete the Script and the Log
Now, go to your Documents folder and delete the actual files:

Open File Explorer and go to Documents.

Find kl.ps1 → Right-click → Delete.

Find kl.txt → Right-click → Delete.

